## 5. JWT Authentication Design

### Token Structure

| Token | Lifetime | Storage | Purpose |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Access Token** | 15–60 minutes | Flutter in-memory | API request authorization |
| **Refresh Token** | 30 days | Flutter secure storage + DB `refresh_tokens` | Renew expired access tokens |

### Login Flow (Mobile App — OTP Based)

```
Student opens app
       │
       ▼
Enters mobile number
       │
       ▼
POST /api/auth/send-otp  ──────────────────▶  Server generates OTP
   { mobile: "9876543210" }                    Stores hashed OTP in `otp_verifications`
                                               Sends SMS via gateway
       │
       ▼
Student enters 6-digit OTP
       │
       ▼
POST /api/auth/verify-otp  ─────────────────▶  Server verifies OTP
   { mobile: "...", otp: "123456" }            Checks expiry + attempts
                                               If new user → creates `students` record
                                               Generates JWT access + refresh tokens
                                               Stores refresh token in `refresh_tokens`
       │
       ▼
App receives tokens ◀───────────────────────── Response:
   { access_token, refresh_token,               { access_token: "eyJ...",
     expires_in, user }                           refresh_token: "abc...",
                                                  expires_in: 3600,
       │                                          user: { id, name, ... } }
       ▼
Stores access_token in memory
Stores refresh_token in secure storage
```

### Token Validation (Every API Request)

```
Flutter sends request
   Authorization: Bearer <access_token>
       │
       ▼
JWT Middleware validates token
   - Checks signature (HS256/RS256)
   - Checks expiration (`exp` claim)
   - Extracts student_id from `sub` claim
       │
   ┌───┴───┐
   │Valid  │Invalid/Expired
   │       │
   ▼       ▼
Process    Return 401 Unauthorized
request    Flutter triggers refresh flow
```

### Token Refresh Flow

```
Access token expired (401 response)
       │
       ▼
POST /api/auth/refresh
   { refresh_token: "abc..." }
       │
       ▼
Server checks `refresh_tokens` table
   - Token exists?
   - Not revoked?  (revoked_at IS NULL)
   - Not expired?  (expires_at > now)
       │
   ┌───┴───┐
   │Valid  │Invalid
   │       │
   ▼       ▼
Generate   Return 401
new        → User must
access     re-login
token
   │
   ▼
Return new access_token
(Optionally rotate refresh_token)
```

### Admin Panel Auth (Separate)

The admin panel uses **Laravel's standard session-based authentication** (email + password), not JWT. This keeps the admin panel secure with CSRF tokens and server-side sessions.

---

## 6. Admin Panel Data Flow

### Example 1: Admin Creates a New Course

```
Admin fills course form (title, icon, color, category, price, description, thumbnail)
       │
       ▼
Browser sends POST /content/course
   - Multipart form data (includes thumbnail file)
   - CSRF token in header
       │
       ▼
CourseController@store validates input
       │
       ▼
CourseService->createCourse()
   - Generates slug from title
   - Uploads thumbnail → file storage
   - Creates record in `courses` table
       │
       ▼
ActivityLogService->log('course.created', $course)
       │
       ▼
Redirect back with success flash message
```

### Example 2: Admin Uploads Notes/Videos

```
Admin clicks "Upload Notes" → selects PDF files
       │
       ▼
AJAX POST /api/admin/notes/upload
   - Files in multipart
   - subject_id, folder_id
       │
       ▼
NoteController@upload
       │
       ▼
NoteService->uploadFiles()
   - For each file:
     - Store file to disk/S3
     - Create record in `notes` table
     - Set is_free = false by default
     - Set sort_order = next available
       │
       ▼
Return JSON { success: true, notes: [...] }
```

### Example 3: Admin Edits Content Item Details

```
Admin clicks "Edit Details" icon on a note/video
       │
       ▼
Modal opens with title, description, thumbnail, sort_order fields
       │
       ▼
PUT /api/admin/notes/{id}  (or /videos/{id} or /qa-papers/{id})
   { title, description, sort_order, thumbnail (optional file) }
       │
       ▼
NoteService->update($id, $data)  (or VideoService / QaPaperService)
   - Updates the record in the respective table
   - Replaces thumbnail if new one uploaded
       │
       ▼
Return success response
```

### Example 4: Admin Toggles Content Free/Paid

```
Admin toggles the free/paid switch on a note/video/QA paper
       │
       ▼
PATCH /api/admin/notes/{id}/access  (or /videos/{id} or /qa-papers/{id})
   { is_free: true }
       │
       ▼
NoteService->toggleAccess($id, $isFree)  (or VideoService / QaPaperService)
   - Updates `is_free` field in the respective table
       │
       ▼
Return success response
```

### Example 5: Admin Deletes a Course

```
Admin clicks delete → confirms in SweetAlert
       │
       ▼
DELETE /content/course/{id}
       │
       ▼
CourseService->deleteCourse($id)
   - Check for active enrollments (prevent if exists)
   - Cascade delete: subjects → note_folders/video_folders/qa_paper_folders → notes/videos/qa_papers → quizzes
   - Remove all uploaded files from storage
   - Log activity
       │
       ▼
Redirect with success or error message
```

---

## 7. Flutter App Data Flow

### Example 1: Student Login & Token Management

```
App opens → Splash Screen
       │
       ▼
Check secure storage for refresh_token
       │
   ┌───┴───┐
   │Exists │No token
   │       │
   ▼       ▼
POST       Show Login
/api/auth  Screen
/refresh
   │
   ┌───┴───┐
   │Valid  │Invalid
   │       │
   ▼       ▼
Navigate   Show Login
to Home    Screen
```

### Example 2: Student Browses and Purchases Content

```
Home Screen → Tap "Explore"
       │
       ▼
GET /api/standards
   Authorization: Bearer <token>
       │
       ▼
API returns categories with standards:
   { categories: [{ name: "Primary", standards: [...] }, ...] }
       │
       ▼
Student taps "Standard 10"
       │
       ▼
GET /api/standards/{id}/subjects
       │
       ▼
API returns subjects with pricing:
   { course: { name, price }, subjects: [{ name, price, content_counts }, ...] }
       │
       ▼
Student selects "Full Course" or picks subjects → adds to cart
       │
       ▼
Cart stored locally (Flutter state)
       │
       ▼
Checkout → POST /api/orders
   { course_id, type: "full_course", subjects: [...], payment_method: "upi" }
       │
       ▼
Server creates `enrollment` (pending) + `enrollment_subjects` + initiates payment
       │
       ▼
Payment gateway callback → Server updates `payments.status` + `enrollments.status`
       │
       ▼
App polls or receives push → Enrollment confirmed → Content unlocked
```

### Example 3: Student Takes a Quiz

```
Student opens quiz list for a subject
       │
       ▼
GET /api/subjects/{id}/quizzes
       │
       ▼
Returns available quizzes with attempts info:
   [{ id, title, difficulty, duration, totalQuestions, maxAttempts, usedAttempts, isFree }]
       │
       ▼
Student taps quiz → checks access (enrolled or free)
       │
       ▼
POST /api/quizzes/{id}/start
   → Creates `quiz_attempts` record → Returns questions + options
       │
       ▼
Student answers questions (state managed locally)
       │
       ▼
POST /api/quizzes/{id}/submit
   { attempt_id, answers: [{ question_id, selected_option_id }, ...] }
       │
       ▼
Server evaluates answers → Updates `quiz_attempts` score → Creates `quiz_answers`
       │
       ▼
Returns result: { score, total, percentage, passed, correctAnswers }
```

### Example 4: Student Watches a Video

```
Student navigates to subject content
       │
       ▼
GET /api/subjects/{id}/videos
   → Returns video_folders tree with video items
       │
       ▼
Student taps a video
       │
       ▼
Check access:
   - is_free = true → play immediately
   - is_free = false → check enrollment
       │
       ▼
GET /api/videos/{id}/stream-url
   → Returns signed/temporary video URL (if authorized)
       │
       ▼
Flutter video player loads and plays the URL
```

