## 11. Storage Strategy

To ensure scalable file management (whether Local or AWS S3), all physical files (videos, notes, PDFs, thumbnails) must follow a strict hierarchical folder structure tied to their parent entities.

**Directory Structure Pattern**:
```text
storage/app/public/
   └── courses/
       └── {course_id}/
           └── subjects/
               └── {subject_id}/
                   ├── videos/
                   │   ├── intro.mp4
                   │   └── lecture1.mp4
                   ├── notes/
                   │   ├── chapter1.pdf
                   │   └── syllabus.pdf
                   ├── qa_papers/
                   │   └── 2024_board.pdf
                   └── thumbnails/
                       └── subject_cover.jpg
```

**Benefits of this approach**:
1. **Easy Cleanup**: If a subject or course is deleted, one command deletes the entire subtree (`Storage::deleteDirectory("courses/{course_id}")`).
2. **Organization**: Prevents reaching OS/bucket limits on single folders.
3. **Database Mapping**: The `file_path` column in `notes`, `videos`, and `qa_papers` tables will store the relative path: `courses/10/subjects/5/videos/intro.mp4`.

---

> [!NOTE]
> **Total Tables**: 23 tables across 5 modules
> **Design Principles**: Normalized to 3NF, proper foreign keys, separate admin/student tables, dedicated tables per content type, separate order/enrollment flows.
